comment: Ibaka (OKC) sets the screen on Mbah a Moute (LAC) and gives him room to avoid the contact.

Griffin (LAC) maintains legal guarding position as he contests Westbrook's (OKC) layup attempt. Westbrook does not kick his leg out unnaturally and the contact by his foot to Griffin is considered incidental and part of a normal basketball play.
Jordan (LAC) sets the screen on Durant (OKC) and gives him room to avoid the contact.
RHH shows that Adams (OKC) makes body to body contact that affects Paul's (LAC) RSBQ as he attempts to split the trap. As a result of the body contact, Paul makes incidental contact with Adams' face.

LATR and L-SLASH shows Waiters (OKC) grabs and pulls Redick's (LAC) jersey slightly, affecting his FOM away from the ball as he goes around the screen. The jersey pull takes place before Redick catches, plants and takes the shot.
Griffin (LAC) firms up as he sets the screen on Waiters (OKC) and gives him room to avoid the contact.
Adams (OKC) sets the screen on Paul (LAC) and gives him room to avoid the contact.
Roberson (OKC) maintains legal guarding position and does not affect Redick's (LAC) RSBQ on the drive to the basket.
Redick (LAC) gathers and legally takes a step with his left foot and then right foot. The ball is then stripped when he pivots.
Westbrook (OKC) cleanly strips the ball from Redick (LAC).
Redick (LAC) grabs Westbrook (OKC) and affects his ability to retrieve the loose ball.
After the ball becomes loose, Mbah a Moute (LAC) and Westbrook (OKC) make incidental foot to foot contact causing Westbrook to fall to the floor.
L-SLASH shows that as he falls to the ground, Westbrook (OKC) undercuts Paul (LAC) and makes contact with his left leg that affects his movement to the basket on the made layup attempt.
Ibaka (OKC) extends his arms as he sets the screen on Mbah a Moute (LAC) without giving him room to avoid the contact.
Mbah a Moute (LAC) maintains legal guarding position as he defends Durant's (OKC) drive and shot attempt.
Durant (OKC) cleanly blocks Paul's (LAC) jump shot attempt. Any "high-five" contact after the block is considered incidental.
